[[File:A small cup of coffee.JPG|thumb|200px|A cup of coffee]]
'''[https://internationalcoffeeday.org/ International Coffee Day]''' is an [[List of food days|occasion]] that is used to promote and celebrate [[coffee]] as a beverage, with events now occurring in places across the world. The first official date was 1 October 2015, as agreed by the [[International Coffee Organization]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://icocoffeeorg.tumblr.com/post/128101688395/how-are-you-celebrating-international-coffee-day |title=How are you celebrating International Coffee Day? |work=International Coffee Organization blog |accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> and was launched in Milan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://scae.com/news-and-events/international-coffee-day |title=International Coffee Day |publisher=Speciality Coffee Association of Europe |accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref> This day is also used to promote [[fair trade coffee]] and to raise awareness for the plight of the coffee growers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Film Highlights Coffee Industry|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/6733125.stm|accessdate=4 October 2011|work=BBC News|date=June 8, 2007}}</ref> On this day, many businesses offer free or discounted cups of coffee.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pflaumer|first=Alicia|title=National Coffee Day: Where can you get your free cup today?|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/Business/new-economy/2010/0929/National-Coffee-Day-Where-can-you-get-your-free-cup-today|accessdate=29 September 2011|newspaper=Christian Science Monitor}}</ref>  Some businesses share coupons and special deals with their loyal followers via [[social networking]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Monty|first=Chris|title=National Coffee Day: Perk Up, Time To Celebrate!|url=http://www.blippitt.com/national-coffee-day-perk-up-time-to-celebrate/|accessdate=8 October 2011|newspaper=Blippitt Internet News Magazine|date=29 September 2011}}</ref>  Some greeting card companies sell National Coffee Day greeting cards as well as free e-cards.<ref>{{cite web|title=Send a Free Coffee Day Card|url=http://www.punchbowl.com/ecards/national-coffee-day|work=International Coffee Day|publisher=Punchbowl|accessdate=8 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Happy National Coffee Day September 29 Greeting Card|url=http://www.greetingcarduniverse.com/-Happy+National+Coffee+Day+September+29-greeting+card-742867|work=International Coffee Day|publisher=Greeting Card Universe|accessdate=8 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Free International Coffee Day eCard|url=http://www.doozycards.com/international-coffee-day|work=International Coffee Day|publisher=Doozycards|accessdate=28 September 2016}}</ref>

== History ==
At a meeting on 3–7 March 2014,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ilovebuttercoffee.com/national-coffee-day-history/#history-2|title=National Coffee Day vs International Coffee Day {{!}} The History Story|date=2016-12-03|newspaper=Bulletproof Coffee Fan Club|language=en-US|access-date=2016-12-10}}</ref> a decision was taken by the International Coffee Organization to launch the first official International Coffee Day in Milan as part of [[Expo 2015]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.expo2015news.org/expo2015-il-progetto/958/international-coffee-day-at-the-expo-2015/ |title=Event: International Coffee Day at the Expo 2015 |publisher=[[Expo 2015]] |date=12 March 2015 |accessdate=28 September 2015}}</ref>

Various events have been held, called '''Coffee Day''' or '''National Coffee Day''', with many of these on or around September 29.<ref>{{cite news|last=Katz |first=Neil|date=September 29, 2010|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/national-coffee-day-do-you-know-whats-in-your-joe/|title=National Coffee Day: Do You Know What's in Your Joe?|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref>

The exact origin of International Coffee Day is unknown. An event was first promoted in Japan in 1983 by The All Japan Coffee Association (全日本コーヒー協会).<ref>[[:ja:全日本コーヒー協会]], Retrieved 4 October 2011{{Better source|reason=per WP:CIRCULAR|date=August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Coffee Day – All Japan Coffee Association|url=http://ajca.or.jp/about/day|work=International Coffee Day|publisher=All Japan Coffee Association|accessdate=4 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Coffee Day (10.1) |url=http://www.ffortune.net/life/ocha/coffee.htm |work=International Coffee Day |publisher=ffortune |accessdate=4 October 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110819064504/http://www.ffortune.net/life/ocha/coffee.htm |archivedate=August 19, 2011 }}</ref> In the United States "National Coffee Day" was mentioned publicly as early as 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/12666/perk-its-international-coffee-day |title=Perk Up: It's International Coffee Day! Perk Up: It's International Coffee Day!|first=Adrienne |last=Crezo|publisher=Mental Floss|date=September 29, 2012}}</ref> The name "International Coffee Day" was first used by the [[Southern Food and Beverage Museum]], which called a press conference on October 3, 2009 to celebrate it and to announce the first New Orleans Coffee Festival.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jones |first=Christopher |title=Today is International Coffee Day! |url=http://sportsnola.com/today-is-international-coffee-day/ |accessdate=28 September 2015 |work=sportsNOLA (Louisiana Sports News) |date=September 29, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150929032605/http://sportsnola.com/today-is-international-coffee-day/ |archivedate=29 September 2015 |df= }}</ref> It was promoted in China by the [[International Coffee Organization]], first celebrated in 1997, and made into an annual celebration in early April 2001.<ref name="International Coffee Day">{{cite web|title=International Coffee Day|url=http://pr.shisu.edu.cn/s/19/t/38/0b/c9/info3017.htm|work=International Coffee Day|publisher=Shanghai International Studies University|accessdate=4 October 2011}}</ref> Taiwan first celebrated International Coffee Day in 2009.<ref name="easy.sina.com.tw">{{cite news|url=http://easy.sina.com.tw/news/article_newsid-45558.html|title=2009台灣國際咖啡節  雲林飄香啡比尋常  咖啡四寶等您來發掘 - 新浪休閒|last=|first=|date=November 3, 2009|work=|newspaper=Sina News Taiwan|via=|accessdate=4 October 2011}}</ref> Nepal first celebrated National Coffee Day on November 17, 2005.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nepal marks 6th national coffee day|url=http://www.thehimalayantimes.com/fullNews.php?headline=Nepal+marks+6th+national+coffee+day&NewsID=266001|accessdate=12 October 2011|newspaper=Himalayan Times|date=2010-11-17}}</ref> Indonesia, which first celebrated National Coffee Day on August 17, 2006, celebrates it on the same day as Indonesia's Independence Day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehamburgexpress.com/content/view/1736/54/|title=Indonesia Celebrates Independence Day with Coffee Tasting|last=|first=|date=2009-10-13|work=|newspaper=The Hamburg Express|via=|accessdate=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402203915/http://www.thehamburgexpress.com/content/view/1736/54/#|archive-date=2012-04-02|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>

