{{Infobox medical condition (new) | synonyms = PLCG2-associated antibody deficiency and immune dysregulation | name = PLAID syndrome | image = | caption = | pronounce = | field = | DiseasesDB = | ICD9 = | ICDO = | MedlinePlus = | eMedicineSubj = | eMedicineTopic = | MeshID = | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }}
'''PLAID syndrome''' is a inherited condition characterised by [[antibody deficiency]] and [[immune dysregulation]], first described in 2012. The name is an acronym of "[[PLCG2]]-associated antibody deficiency and immune dysregulation". It is characterised by [[cold urticaria|cold-induced urticaria]], [[autoimmunity]], [[atopy]] and [[humoral immune deficiency]].<ref name=Milner2015>{{cite journal|last1=Milner|first1=JD|title=PLAID: a Syndrome of Complex Patterns of Disease and Unique Phenotypes.|journal=Journal of clinical immunology|date=August 2015|volume=35|issue=6|pages=527–30|doi=10.1007/s10875-015-0177-x|pmid=26206677|pmc=4575258}}</ref>
[[Familial cold urticaria]] presents similar symptoms.<ref name=Kanazawa2015>{{cite journal|last1=Kanazawa|first1=N|title=Hereditary disorders presenting with urticaria.|journal=Immunology and allergy clinics of North America|date=February 2014|volume=34|issue=1|pages=169–79|doi=10.1016/j.iac.2013.08.001|pmid=24262697}}</ref>
